ortugal":"France, Vila Real, Portugal"},"nl":{"1370–1415":"1370–1415","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1365–1415":"1365–1415","1394–1465":"1394–1465","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1335–1395":"1335–1395","1415":"1415","about 1382":"circa 1382","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1465":"1465","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England, UK":"Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kent, England":"Kent, England","France, Vila Real, Portugal":"France, Vila Real, Portugal"},"en":{"1370–1415":"1370–1415","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1365–1415":"1365–1415","1394–1465":"1394–1465","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1335–1395":"1335–1395","1415":"1415","about 1382":"about 1382","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1465":"1465","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England, UK":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","France, Vila Real, Portugal":"France, Vila Real, Portugal","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ballard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>ballard</i> ‘bald-headed man’ (compare   Bald   3).","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Balhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>bal</i>, presumably meaning ‘torment, spitefulness’, and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’. Compare   Ballor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ballon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Sergio, Alfonso, Cesar, Conchita, Emigdio, Enrique, Felipe, Francisco, Jose Luis, Julio, Ruben.  Jewish Hyman, Isadore.","Spanish and Galician: unexplained.","French and English (Middlesex): from the Old French personal name <i>Ballon</i>, <i>Ballun</i>, derived from the oblique stem of ancient Germanic <i>Ballo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>bal</i>, presumably meaning ‘torment, spitefulness’ (see   Ballard  )."]},{"name":"Bald","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Inge, Karl-Heinz, Konrad, Kurt, Otto.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i>, or a short form of various compound names such as   Baldwin  , formed with the first element <i>bald</i> ‘bold, strong’.","Scottish and English: from the Norman personal name <i>Bald(e)</i>, <i>Baud(e)</i>, occasionally <i>Bold</i>, a short form of the common ancient Germanic personal names   Baldwin   or <i>Baldric</i>, or possibly a survival of Old English <i>Beald</i> (compare   Balding  ); the relevant element in each of these is <i>b(e)ald</i> ‘brave’. As a hereditary surname it seems to have died out in England but survives in Scotland."]},{"name":"Ballor","meanings":["Altered form of French   Ballard   2, reflecting the characteristic Canadian and American French rounding of the <i>-ard</i> ending. It is found mainly in MI."]},{"name":"Bollard","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire) and Irish: probably a variant of   Ballard  . According to MacLysaght, this is a surname of Dutch origin which was taken to Ireland early in the 18th century.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bolohard</i>, composed of the elements <i>bolo</i> ‘friend, brother’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’."]}]},{"name":"Gregory","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Latin <i>Gregorius</i> from the post-classical Greek name <i>Gregōrios</i> ‘watchful’ (a derivative of <i>gregōrein</i> ‘to watch, be vigilant’). The name was a very popular one among the early Christians, who were mindful of the injunction ‘be sober, be vigilant’ (1 Peter 5:8). It was borne by a number of early saints. The most important, in honour of whom the name was often bestowed from medieval times onwards, were Gregory of Nazianzen (  <i>c.</i>329–90 ), Gregory of Nyssa (  d. <i>c.</i>395 ), Gregory of Tours (  538–94 ), and  Pope Gregory the Great  (  <i>c.</i>540–604 ). A famous bearer of the name in modern times is the film star  Gregory Peck  (  1916–2003 ). The name has traditionally been popular in Scotland, where it is often found in the form  <b>Gregor</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Gregory Ballard was born in 1370, in Buckinghamshire, England, his father, Thomas Ballard MP, was 41 and his mother, Alice Gregory, was 35. He had at least 1 son with Catherine Gregory. He died in 1415, in France, Vila Real, Portugal, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1370–1415":"1370–1415","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1365–1415":"1365–1415","1394–1465":"1394–1465","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1335–1395":"1335–1395","1415":"1415","about 1382":"umbes 1382","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1465":"1465","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England, UK":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","France, Vila Real, Portugal":"France, Vila Real, Portugal"},"fi":{"1370–1415":"1370–1415","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1365–1415":"1365–1415","1394–1465":"1394–1465","1330–1382":"1330–1382","133